{"title_page": "Cohen's h", "text_new": "In [[statistics]], '''Cohen's ''h''''', popularized by [[Jacob Cohen (statistician)|Jacob Cohen]], is a measure of distance between two proportions or [[probability|probabilities]]. Cohen's ''h'' has several related uses: \n* It can be used to describe the difference between two proportions as \"small\", \"medium\", or \"large\".\n* It can be used to determine if the difference between two proportions is \"[[clinical significance|meaningful]]\".\n* It can be used in calculating the [[sample size determination|sample size]] for a future study.\n\nWhen measuring differences between proportions, Cohen's ''h'' can be used in conjunction with [[statistical hypothesis testing|hypothesis testing]]. A \"[[statistical significance|statistically significant]]\" difference between two proportions is understood to mean that, given the data, it is likely that there is a difference in the population proportions. However, this difference might be too small to be meaningful\u2014the statistically significant result does not tell us the size of the difference. Cohen's ''h'', on the other hand, quantifies the size of the difference, allowing us to decide if the difference is meaningful.\n\n== Uses ==\nResearchers have used Cohen's ''h'' as follows.\n* Describe the differences in proportions using the [[rule of thumb]] criteria set out by Cohen.<ref name=\"Cohen 1988\">{{cite book | title=Statistical Power Analysis for the Behavioral Sciences | author=Cohen, Jacob | year=1988 | edition=2nd}}</ref> Namely, ''h'' = 0.2 is a \"small\" difference, ''h'' = 0.5 is a \"medium\" difference, and ''h'' = 0.8 is a \"large\" difference.<ref>{{cite journal | title=The Patient Health Questionnaire-9 for measuring depressive symptoms among the general population in Hong Kong | author=Yu, Xiaonan | journal=Comprehensive Psychiatry | year=2012 | volume=53 | pages=95\u2013102 | doi=10.1016/j.comppsych.2010.11.002 | display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Characteristics of Youths With Hearing Loss Admitted to Substance Abuse Treatment | author=Titus, Janet C. | journal=Journal of Deaf Studies and Deaf Education |date=February 2008  | doi=10.1093/deafed/enm068 | display-authors=etal | volume=13 | pages=336\u2013350}}</ref>\n* Only discuss differences that have ''h'' greater than some threshold value, such as 0.2.<ref name=\"Reavley\">{{cite journal | title=Stigmatising attitudes towards people with mental disorders: Changes in Australia over 8 years | author=Reavley, Nicola J. | journal=Psychiatry Research | year=2012 | volume=197 | pages=302\u2013306 | doi=10.1016/j.psychres.2012.01.011 | display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n* When the sample size is so large that many differences are likely to be statistically significant, Cohen's ''h'' identifies \"meaningful\", \"[[clinical significance|clinically meaningful]]\", or \"practically significant\" differences.<ref name=\"Reavley\"/><ref>{{cite journal | title=Intentions and helpfulness beliefs about first aid responses for young people with mental disorders: Findings from two Australian national surveys of youth | author=Yap, Marie Bee Hui | journal=Journal of Affective Disorders | year=2012 | volume=136 | pages=430\u2013442 | doi=10.1016/j.jad.2011.11.006 | display-authors=etal | pmid=22137764}}</ref>\n\n== Calculation ==\nGiven a probability or proportion ''p'', between 0 and 1, its \"arcsine transformation\" is\n\n: <math>\\phi = 2 \\arcsin \\sqrt{p}</math>\n\n{{Further|Binomial proportion confidence interval}}\n\nGiven two proportions, <math>p_1</math> and <math>p_2</math>, ''h'' is defined as the difference between their arcsine transformations.<ref name=\"Cohen 1988\"/> Namely,\n\n: <math>h = \\phi_1 - \\phi_2</math>\n\nThis is also sometimes called \"directional ''h''\" because, in addition to showing the magnitude of the difference, it shows which of the two proportions is greater.\n\nOften, researchers mean \"nondirectional ''h''\", which is just the absolute value of the directional ''h'':\n\n: <math>h = \\left| \\phi_1 - \\phi_2 \\right|</math>\n\nIn [[R (programming language)|R]], Cohen's ''h'' can be calculated using the <code>ES.h</code> function in the <code>pwr</code> package.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cran.r-project.org/package=pwr | title=pwr: Basic Functions for Power Analysis | date=2015 | author=Champely, Stephane}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretation ==\nCohen<ref name=\"Cohen 1988\"/> provides the following descriptive interpretations of ''h'' as a [[rule of thumb]]:\n* ''h'' = 0.20: \"small effect size\".\n* ''h'' = 0.50: \"medium effect size\".\n* ''h'' = 0.80: \"large effect size\".\n\nCohen cautions that: \n{{quote|As before, the reader is counseled to avoid the use of these conventions, if he can, in favor of exact values provided by theory or experience in the specific area in which he is working.}}\n\nNevertheless, many researchers do use these conventions as given.\n\n== Sample size calculation ==\n{{Empty section|date=June 2015}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Mathematics}}\n* [[Estimation statistics]]\n* [[Clinical significance]]\n* [[Cohen's d]]\n* [[Odds ratio]]\n* [[Effect size]]\n* [[Sample size determination]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Medical research studies}}\n{{Statistics}}\n{{Experimental design}}\n\n[[Category:Effect size]]\n[[Category:Statistical hypothesis testing]]\n[[Category:Medical statistics]]\n[[Category:Clinical research]]\n[[Category:Clinical trials]]\n[[Category:Biostatistics]]\n[[Category:Sampling (statistics)]]\n", "text_old": "In [[statistics]], '''Cohen's h''', popularized by [[Jacob Cohen (statistician)|Jacob Cohen]], is a measure of distance between two proportions or [[probability|probabilities]]. Cohen's h has several related uses: \n* It can be used to describe the difference between two proportions as \"small\", \"medium\", or \"large\".\n* It can be used to determine if the difference between two proportions is \"[[clinical significance|meaningful]]\".\n* It can be used in calculating the [[sample size determination|sample size]] for a future study.\n\nWhen measuring differences between proportions, Cohen's h can be used in conjunction with [[statistical hypothesis testing|hypothesis testing]]. A \"[[statistical significance|statistically significant]]\" difference between two proportions is understood to mean that, given the data, it is likely that there is a difference in the population proportions. However, this difference might be too small to be meaningful\u2014the statistically significant result does not tell us the size of the difference. Cohen's h, on the other hand, quantifies the size of the difference, allowing us to decide if the difference is meaningful.\n\n== Uses ==\nResearchers have used Cohen's h as follows.\n* Describe the differences in proportions using the [[rule of thumb]] criteria set out by Cohen.<ref name=\"Cohen 1988\">{{cite book | title=Statistical Power Analysis for the Behavioral Sciences | author=Cohen, Jacob | year=1988 | edition=2nd}}</ref> Namely, ''h'' = 0.2 is a \"small\" difference, ''h'' = 0.5 is a \"medium\" difference, and ''h'' = 0.8 is a \"large\" difference.<ref>{{cite journal | title=The Patient Health Questionnaire-9 for measuring depressive symptoms among the general population in Hong Kong | author=Yu, Xiaonan | journal=Comprehensive Psychiatry | year=2012 | volume=53 | pages=95\u2013102 | doi=10.1016/j.comppsych.2010.11.002 | display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | title=Characteristics of Youths With Hearing Loss Admitted to Substance Abuse Treatment | author=Titus, Janet C. | journal=Journal of Deaf Studies and Deaf Education |date=February 2008  | doi=10.1093/deafed/enm068 | display-authors=etal | volume=13 | pages=336\u2013350}}</ref>\n* Only discuss differences that have ''h'' greater than some threshold value, such as 0.2.<ref name=\"Reavley\">{{cite journal | title=Stigmatising attitudes towards people with mental disorders: Changes in Australia over 8 years | author=Reavley, Nicola J. | journal=Psychiatry Research | year=2012 | volume=197 | pages=302\u2013306 | doi=10.1016/j.psychres.2012.01.011 | display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n* When the sample size is so large that many differences are likely to be statistically significant, Cohen's h identifies \"meaningful\", \"[[clinical significance|clinically meaningful]]\", or \"practically significant\" differences.<ref name=\"Reavley\"/><ref>{{cite journal | title=Intentions and helpfulness beliefs about first aid responses for young people with mental disorders: Findings from two Australian national surveys of youth | author=Yap, Marie Bee Hui | journal=Journal of Affective Disorders | year=2012 | volume=136 | pages=430\u2013442 | doi=10.1016/j.jad.2011.11.006 | display-authors=etal | pmid=22137764}}</ref>\n\n== Calculation ==\nGiven a probability or proportion ''p'', between 0 and 1, its \"arcsine transformation\" is\n\n: <math>\\phi = 2 \\arcsin \\sqrt{p}</math>\n\n{{Further|Binomial proportion confidence interval}}\n\nGiven two proportions, <math>p_1</math> and <math>p_2</math>, ''h'' is defined as the difference between their arcsine transformations.<ref name=\"Cohen 1988\"/> Namely,\n\n: <math>h = \\phi_1 - \\phi_2</math>\n\nThis is also sometimes called \"directional h\" because, in addition to showing the magnitude of the difference, it shows which of the two proportions is greater.\n\nOften, researchers mean \"nondirectional h\", which is just the absolute value of the directional h:\n\n: <math>h = \\left| \\phi_1 - \\phi_2 \\right|</math>\n\nIn [[R (programming language)|R]], Cohen's h can be calculated using the <code>ES.h</code> function in the <code>pwr</code> package.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://cran.r-project.org/package=pwr | title=pwr: Basic Functions for Power Analysis | date=2015 | author=Champely, Stephane}}</ref>\n\n== Interpretation ==\nCohen<ref name=\"Cohen 1988\"/> provides the following descriptive interpretations of ''h'' as a [[rule of thumb]]:\n* ''h'' = 0.20: \"small effect size\".\n* ''h'' = 0.50: \"medium effect size\".\n* ''h'' = 0.80: \"large effect size\".\n\nCohen cautions that: \n{{quote|As before, the reader is counseled to avoid the use of these conventions, if he can, in favor of exact values provided by theory or experience in the specific area in which he is working.}}\n\nNevertheless, many researchers do use these conventions as given.\n\n== Sample size calculation ==\n{{Empty section|date=June 2015}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Mathematics}}\n* [[Estimation statistics]]\n* [[Clinical significance]]\n* [[Cohen's d]]\n* [[Odds ratio]]\n* [[Effect size]]\n* [[Sample size determination]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Medical research studies}}\n{{Statistics}}\n{{Experimental design}}\n\n[[Category:Effect size]]\n[[Category:Statistical hypothesis testing]]\n[[Category:Medical statistics]]\n[[Category:Clinical research]]\n[[Category:Clinical trials]]\n[[Category:Biostatistics]]\n[[Category:Sampling (statistics)]]\n", "name_user": "Doremo", "label": "safe", "comment": "italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cohen%27s_h"}
{"title_page": "Roman Ruins of Milreu", "text_new": "{{Infobox ancient site\n| name           = Roman Ruins of Milreu\n| native_name    = \n| alternate_name = Roman Ruins of Est\u00f3i\n<!-- image & map -->\n| image          = Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_2017_-_Templo.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = The rear of the water temple\n| map            = \n| map_type       = \n| map_caption    = \n| map_size       = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|37|5|42.2|N|7|54|14.3|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Faro (district)|Faro]], [[Algarve]], [[Portugal]]\n| type           = [[Ruins]]\n| part_of        = \n<!-- stats -->\n| altitude_m     = \n| length         = \n| width          = \n| area           = \n| volume         = \n| diameter       = \n| circumference  = \n| height         = \n| builder        = \n| material       = \n| built          = Between the 1st and 4th centuries AD\n| abandoned      = 10th Century AD\n| epochs         = <!-- actually displays as 'Periods' -->\n| cultures       = [[Roman Empire|Roman]]\n| dependency_of  = \n| occupants      = Roman Paganism, Christianity, Islam\n| event          = \n| discovered     = 1877\n| excavations    = \n| archaeologists = [[Est\u00e1cio da Veiga]]\n| condition      = \n| ownership      = Portuguese Republic\n| management     = \n| public_access  = Public EN2-6, between Coiro da Burra and Estoi, alongside the junction between Faro da Via do Infante, {{convert|9|km|mi}} from Faro\n| website        = \n| notes          = \n<!-- Other -->\n| other_designation =\n}}\nThe '''Roman Ruins of Milreu''' ({{lang-pt|Ruinas Romanas de Milreu}}) are the remains of an important Roman [[villa rustica]] located in the [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] of [[Est\u00f3i]] in the [[Concelho|municipality]] of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]], [[Portugal]], classified as a ''Monumento Nacional'' (National Monument). The Milreu ruins constitute the most prominent and well preserved evidence of Roman presence in the Algarve, and are mainly composed of the remnants of a once luxurious villa with annexed [[thermae]] and several surrounding buildings, including a temple, [[mausoleum]] and industrial and commercial structures.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Rebello, Brito |title=Hemeroteca Municipal de Lisboa. O Occidente: Revista Illustrada de Portugal e do Estrangeiro. Ano IV (96). Lisboa. |date=21 August 1881 |page=189; 190 |url=http://hemerotecadigital.cm-lisboa.pt/OBRAS/Ocidente/1881/N96/N96_master/N96.pdf |accessdate=22 December 2018 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> The archaeological site still preserves part of the once exuberant mosaics (mostly maritime motifs) that decorated the floor and walls of the villa. A 16th century house is also located in the area, alongside an interpretation centre.<ref>{{cite web |author1=KREMER, Maria de Jesus Duran |title=Portugal Romano: Revista de Arqueologia Romana. |url=https://issuu.com/portugalromano/docs/revista |website=ISSUU |accessdate=22 December 2018 |pages=81\u201382 |date=April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe town was first constructed and inhabited in the 1st century,<ref name=\"SIPA\">{{citation |url=http://www.monumentos.gov.pt/Site/APP_PagesUser/SIPA.aspx?id=2883 |title=Ru\u00ednas de Est\u00f3i / Ru\u00ednas de Milreu (IPA.00002883/PT040214040001) |publisher=SIPA \u2013 Sistema de Informa\u00e7\u00e3o para o Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico |editor=SIPA |location= Lisbon, Portugal |language=pt |first=Jo\u00e3o |last=Neto |first2=Ros\u00e1rio |last2= Gordalina |year=2003 |accessdate= 22 August 2018}}</ref> with traces of continuous occupation until the 10th century.<ref name=\"IGESPAR\">{{cite web |url= http://www.patrimoniocultural.gov.pt/pt/patrimonio/patrimonio-imovel/pesquisa-do-patrimonio/classificado-ou-em-vias-de-classificacao/geral/view/70255 |title=Ru\u00ednas de Estoi |editor=IGESPAR |accessdate=22 August 2018 |year=2011 |location= Lisbon, Portugal |publisher=IGESPAR-Instituto de Gest\u00e3o do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico e Arqueol\u00f3gico |language= Portuguese}}</ref> Comparable to a large number of rustic villas in Italy and Spain, Milreu distinguished itself as a luxury complex due to its extensive and pompous mosaic decorations, ancient imperial busts, a temple devoted to a water deity, a stunning garden and winery and oil processing mills.\n\n[[File:Gesamtplan_Milreu.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|left|Map of the urban area of Milreu. Description: A - Residencial building; B - Thermae; C - Olive oil mills; D - Wine House; E - Mausoleum; F - Workers's dwellings; G - Temple; H - Commercial Building; I - Gardened area]]\n\nAt the end of the 3rd century, the house was reorganized around a large central [[peristyle]] with columns, surrounding an open courtyard with garden and thermae.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/> In the 4th century, the entrance of the villa was monumental, with the peristyle and baths having been embellished with mosaics representing marine fauna, while to the south stood an imposing building of worship to an aquatic deity, that in the following century would be transformed into a Paleochristan temple.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nLater excavations emphasized a long tradition of worship in Milreu, demonstrating that after the 6th century the building was transformed into a Christian church; the courtyard was also used as a cemetery during the Muslim occupation.<ref name=IGESPAR/> In the first half of the 10th century, the vaults were ruined at the site and the area was abandoned.<ref name=IGESPAR/>\n[[File:Milreu_Keller_Oelmuehle_01.jpg|upright=1.2|right|thumb|German archaeologists during excavations at Milreu in the late 1990s.]]\nThe construction of the rural house occurred in the 16th century.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nThe ruins were discovered in 1877 by Portuguese archaeologist [[Est\u00e1cio da Veiga]]. The late-19th-century excavations by da Veiga made it possible to unravel mosaic works that were buried beneath the dwelling, as well as wine-processing facilities.\n\nOn June the 1st, 1992, the property was placed under the protection of the ''Instituto Portugu\u00eas do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitet\u00f3nico'' (''Portuguese Institute for Architectural Patrimony'').<ref name=SIPA/><ref>{{citation |publisher=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica |title=Decreto-lei 106F/92 |issue=S\u00e9rie IA, 126 |year=1992 |language=pt}}</ref> The site was included in the 1999 ''Programa de Valoriza\u00e7\u00e3o e Divulga\u00e7\u00e3o Tur\u00edstica'' (''Tourism Appreciation and Dissemination Program''), as part of the ''Itiner\u00e1rios Arqueol\u00f3gicos do Alentejo e Algarve'' project of the ''Minist\u00e9rio do Com\u00e9rcio e Turismo'' and ''Secretaria de Estado da Cultura''.<ref name=SIPA/> On the 23rd of June 2001, a public tender was issued for remodelling the 16th-century rural house, to construct an interpretative centre, which was won by architects Ditza Reis and Pedro Serra Alves.<ref name=SIPA/> Work on the site included civil construction and electrification, excavation, conservation and restoration of the walls. The site was re-inaugurated on 19 November 2003, with the opening of a permanent exposition.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nAs of 20 December 2007, the property was placed under the authority of the ''Dire\u00e7\u00e3o Regional da Cultura do Algarve'' (dispatch 1130/2007; Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica, S\u00e9rie II, 245).<ref name=SIPA/>\n\n==Architecture==\nThe site is located in an isolated rural area, behind a bridge, west of the cemetery and roadway.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nThe site includes a seigniorial house, organized around a central patio, change rooms in the east, temple in the south and agricultural installations. The central patio consisted of a [[peristyle]] with 22 columns.<ref name=SIPA/> A thermal spa includes a sequence of [[apodyterium]], [[frigidarium]], circular bathing pool, [[tepidarium]] and [[caldarium]] decorated with mosaics (one with oblong fish designs).<ref name=SIPA/> The ruins of an aquatic sanctuary include an altar that served as paleo-Christian church, as indicated from the presence of a [[baptismal]] pool and a small [[mausoleum]] on the patio.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nNearby the ruins is the 16th-century rural house, used as an interpretative center, that includes a cylindrical buttresses along the outer corners.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\n==Interpretative Center==\n[[File:Milreu-Gutshaus.JPG|thumb|235px|left|The 16th-century rural farmhouse redesigned to act as the interpretative centre]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Milreu-3.JPG|The exposed walls from the buildings in Milreu\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_-_termas_-_15.11.2017.jpg| Part of the Thermae\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_-_Modelo_do_Templo_-_25.09.2018.jpg|Possible representation of how the temple looked like\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_-_mosaico_fauna_marinha_-_15.11.2017.jpg|Floor mosaic\nFile:Ruinen_von_Milreu.jpg|Wall mosaic\nFile:Detail of the mosaic floor in the peristylum depicting a squid, Roman Villa of Milreu, Est\u00f3i, Portugal (12664407055).jpg|Floor mosaic depicting a squid\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_2017_-_Mosaicos_1.jpg|Mosaics at Milreu \nFile:Retrato de Galieno.jpg|Bust of [[Gallienus]]  \nFile:Busto de uma jovem mulher romana-Milreu.jpg|Bust of a woman at Milreu's interpretation centre \nFile:Ruinas_de_Milreu_-_Busto_de_Agripina_-_15.11.2017.jpg|The bust of [[Agrippina the Younger]] found in the property\nFile:Roman_Ruins_of_Milreu_-_Atrium.jpg|Two standing columns that composed the Peristyles\n\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{citation |publisher=Portugiesisches Institut des arch\u00e4ologischen Patrimoniums |title=Roteiros da Arquelogia portuguesa: Milreu - Ruinen |year=2002 |location=Lisbon, Portugal |language=German}}\n* {{citation |first=Thomas G. |last=Schattner |title=Arch\u00e4ologischer Wegweiser durch Portugal |publisher=Philipp von Zabern |location=Mainz |year=1998 |pages=204\u2013207 |isbn=3-8053-2313-1 |language=pt}}\n* {{citation |first=Felix |last=Teichner |title=Zwischen Land und Meer \u2013 Entre tierra y mar. Studien zur Architektur und Wirtschaftsweise l\u00e4ndlicher Siedlungen im S\u00fcden der r\u00f6mischen Provinz Lusitanien |publisher=Stvdia Lvsitana 3 (MNAR) / Madrider Beitr. (DAI) |year=2008 |isbn=978-84-612-7893-0 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |first=Walter |last=Trillmich |first2=Annette |last2=N\u00fcnnerich-Asmus |title=Hispania Antiqua \u2013 Denkm\u00e4ler der R\u00f6merzeit |publisher=von Zabern |location=Mainz |year=1993 |isbn=3-8053-1547-3 |language=German}}\n* {{citation |last=Botto |first=C. Pereira |contribution= Iconografia parcial das constru\u00e7\u00f5es de Milreu |title=O Archeologo Portugu\u00eas |year=1898 |pages=158 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=Rosa |first=J. Cunha |title=Anais do Municipio da Faro |issue=I |year=1969 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=Veiga |first=S.P.M. Est\u00e1cio da |title=A t\u00e1bua de bronze de Aljustrel |location=Lisbon, Portugal |year=1880 |language=Portuguese}}\n\n[[Category:Roman villas in Portugal]]\n[[Category:National monuments in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Faro, Portugal]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ancient site\n| name           = Roman Ruins of Milreu\n| native_name    = \n| alternate_name = Roman Ruins of Est\u00f3i\n<!-- image & map -->\n| image          = Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_2017_-_Templo.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = The rear of the water temple\n| map            = \n| map_type       = \n| map_caption    = \n| map_size       = \n| coordinates    = {{coord|37|5|42.2|N|7|54|14.3|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location       = [[Faro (district)|Faro]], [[Algarve]], [[Portugal]]\n| type           = [[Ruins]]\n| part_of        = \n<!-- stats -->\n| altitude_m     = \n| length         = \n| width          = \n| area           = \n| volume         = \n| diameter       = \n| circumference  = \n| height         = \n| builder        = \n| material       = \n| built          = Between the 1st and 4th centuries AD\n| abandoned      = 10th Century AD\n| epochs         = <!-- actually displays as 'Periods' -->\n| cultures       = [[Roman Empire|Roman]]\n| dependency_of  = \n| occupants      = Roman Paganism, Christianity, Islam\n| event          = \n| discovered     = 1877\n| excavations    = \n| archaeologists = [[Est\u00e1cio da Veiga]]\n| condition      = \n| ownership      = Portuguese Republic\n| management     = \n| public_access  = Public EN2-6, between Coiro da Burra and Estoi, alongside the junction between Faro da Via do Infante, {{convert|9|km|mi}} from Faro\n| website        = \n| notes          = \n<!-- Other -->\n| other_designation =\n}}\nThe '''Roman Ruins of Milreu''' ({{lang-pt|Ruinas Romanas de Milreu}}) are the remains of an important Roman [[Villa rustica|villa rustica]] located in the [[Freguesia (Portugal)|civil parish]] of [[Est\u00f3i]] in the [[Concelho|municipality]] of [[Faro, Portugal|Faro]], [[Portugal]], classified as a ''Monumento Nacional'' (National Monument). The Milreu ruins constitute the most prominent and well preserved evidence of Roman presence in the Algarve, and are mainly composed of the remnants of a once luxurious villa with annexed [[Thermae|thermae]] and several surrounding buildings, including a temple, [[mausoleum]] and industrial and commercial structures<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Rebello, Brito |title=Hemeroteca Municipal de Lisboa. O Occidente: Revista Illustrada de Portugal e do Estrangeiro. Ano IV (96). Lisboa. |date=21 August 1881 |page=189; 190 |url=http://hemerotecadigital.cm-lisboa.pt/OBRAS/Ocidente/1881/N96/N96_master/N96.pdf |accessdate=22 December 2018 |language=Portuguese}}</ref>. The archaeological site still preserves part of the once exuberant mosaics (mostly maritime motifs) that decorated the floor and walls of the villa. A 16th century house is also located in the area, alongside an interpretation centre.<ref>{{cite web |author1=KREMER, Maria de Jesus Duran |title=Portugal Romano: Revista de Arqueologia Romana. |url=https://issuu.com/portugalromano/docs/revista |website=ISSUU |accessdate=22 December 2018 |pages=81-82 |date=April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe town was first constructed and inhabited in the 1st century,<ref name=\"SIPA\">{{citation |url=http://www.monumentos.gov.pt/Site/APP_PagesUser/SIPA.aspx?id=2883 |title=Ru\u00ednas de Est\u00f3i / Ru\u00ednas de Milreu (IPA.00002883/PT040214040001) |publisher=SIPA \u2013 Sistema de Informa\u00e7\u00e3o para o Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico |editor=SIPA |location= Lisbon, Portugal |language=pt |first=Jo\u00e3o |last=Neto |first2=Ros\u00e1rio |last2= Gordalina |year=2003 |accessdate= 22 August 2018}}</ref> with traces of continuous occupation until the 10th century.<ref name=\"IGESPAR\">{{cite web |url= http://www.patrimoniocultural.gov.pt/pt/patrimonio/patrimonio-imovel/pesquisa-do-patrimonio/classificado-ou-em-vias-de-classificacao/geral/view/70255 |title=Ru\u00ednas de Estoi |editor=IGESPAR |accessdate=22 August 2018 |year=2011 |location= Lisbon, Portugal |publisher=IGESPAR-Instituto de Gest\u00e3o do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitect\u00f3nico e Arqueol\u00f3gico |language= Portuguese}}</ref> Comparable to a large number of rustic villas in Italy and Spain, Milreu distinguished itself as a luxury complex due to its extensive and pompous mosaic decorations, ancient imperial busts, a temple devoted to a water deity, a stunning garden and winery and oil processing mills.\n\n[[File:Gesamtplan_Milreu.jpg|thumb |upright=1.2|left|Map of the urban area of Milreu. Description: A - Residencial building; B - Thermae; C - Olive oil mills; D - Wine House; E - Mausoleum; F - Workers's dwellings; G - Temple; H - Commercial Building; I - Gardened area]]\n\nAt the end of the 3rd century, the house was reorganized around a large central [[peristyle]] with columns, surrounding an open courtyard with garden and thermae.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/> In the 4th century, the entrance of the villa was monumental, with the peristyle and baths having been embellished with mosaics representing marine fauna, while to the south stood an imposing building of worship to an aquatic deity, that in the following century would be transformed into a Paleochristan temple.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nLater excavations emphasized a long tradition of worship in Milreu, demonstrating that after the 6th century the building was transformed into a Christian church; the courtyard was also used as a cemetery during the Muslim occupation.<ref name=IGESPAR/> In the first half of the 10th century, the vaults were ruined at the site and the area was abandoned.<ref name=IGESPAR/>\n[[File:Milreu_Keller_Oelmuehle_01.jpg|upright=1.2|right|thumb|German archaeologists during excavations at Milreu in the late 1990's.]]\nThe construction of the rural house occurred in the 16th century.<ref name=SIPA/><ref name=IGESPAR/>\n\nThe ruins were discovered in 1877 by Portuguese archaeologist [[Est\u00e1cio da Veiga]]. The late-19th-century excavations by da Veiga made it possible to unravel mosaic works that were buried beneath the dwelling, as well as wine-processing facilities.\n\nOn June the 1st, 1992, the property was placed under the protection of the ''Instituto Portugu\u00eas do Patrim\u00f3nio Arquitet\u00f3nico'' (''Portuguese Institute for Architectural Patrimony'').<ref name=SIPA/><ref>{{citation |publisher=Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica |title=Decreto-lei 106F/92 |issue=S\u00e9rie IA, 126 |year=1992 |language=pt}}</ref> The site was included in the 1999 ''Programa de Valoriza\u00e7\u00e3o e Divulga\u00e7\u00e3o Tur\u00edstica'' (''Tourism Appreciation and Dissemination Program''), as part of the ''Itiner\u00e1rios Arqueol\u00f3gicos do Alentejo e Algarve'' project of the ''Minist\u00e9rio do Com\u00e9rcio e Turismo'' and ''Secretaria de Estado da Cultura''.<ref name=SIPA/> On the 23rd of June 2001, a public tender was issued for remodelling the 16th-century rural house, to construct an interpretative centre, which was won by architects Ditza Reis and Pedro Serra Alves.<ref name=SIPA/> Work on the site included civil construction and electrification, excavation, conservation and restoration of the walls. The site was re-inaugurated on 19 November 2003, with the opening of a permanent exposition.<ref name=SIPA/> \n\nAs of 20 December 2007, the property was placed under the authority of the ''Dire\u00e7\u00e3o Regional da Cultura do Algarve'' (dispatch 1130/2007; Di\u00e1rio da Rep\u00fablica, S\u00e9rie II, 245).<ref name=SIPA/>\n\n==Architecture==\nThe site is located in an isolated rural area, behind a bridge, west of the cemetery and roadway.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nThe site includes a seigniorial house, organized around a central patio, change rooms in the east, temple in the south and agricultural installations. The central patio consisted of a [[peristyle]] with 22 columns.<ref name=SIPA/> A thermal spa includes a sequence of [[apodyterium]], [[frigidarium]], circular bathing pool, [[tepidarium]] and [[caldarium]] decorated with mosaics (one with oblong fish designs).<ref name=SIPA/> The ruins of an aquatic sanctuary include an altar that served as paleo-Christian church, as indicated from the presence of a [[baptismal]] pool and a small [[mausoleum]] on the patio.<ref name=SIPA/>\n\nNearby the ruins is the 16th-century rural house, used as an interpretative center, that includes a cylindrical buttresses along the outer corners.<ref name=SIPA/> \n\n==Interpretative Center==\n[[File:Milreu-Gutshaus.JPG|thumb|235px|left|The 16th-century rural farmhouse redesigned to act as the interpretative centre]]\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Milreu-3.JPG|The exposed walls from the buildings in Milreu\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_-_termas_-_15.11.2017.jpg| Part of the Thermae\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_-_Modelo_do_Templo_-_25.09.2018.jpg|Possible representation of how the temple looked like\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_-_mosaico_fauna_marinha_-_15.11.2017.jpg|Floor mosaic\nFile:Ruinen_von_Milreu.jpg|Wall mosaic\nFile:Detail of the mosaic floor in the peristylum depicting a squid, Roman Villa of Milreu, Est\u00f3i, Portugal (12664407055).jpg|Floor mosaic depicting a squid\nFile:Ruinas_Romanas_de_Milreu_2017_-_Mosaicos_1.jpg|Mosaics at Milreu \nFile:Retrato de Galieno.jpg|Bust of [[Gallienus]]  \nFile:Busto de uma jovem mulher romana-Milreu.jpg|Bust of a woman at Milreu's interpretation centre \nFile:Ruinas_de_Milreu_-_Busto_de_Agripina_-_15.11.2017.jpg|The bust of [[Agrippina the Younger]] found in the property\nFile:Roman_Ruins_of_Milreu_-_Atrium.jpg|Two standing columns that composed the Peristyles\n\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{citation |publisher=Portugiesisches Institut des arch\u00e4ologischen Patrimoniums |title=Roteiros da Arquelogia portuguesa: Milreu - Ruinen |year=2002 |location=Lisbon, Portugal |language=German}}\n* {{citation |first=Thomas G. |last=Schattner |title=Arch\u00e4ologischer Wegweiser durch Portugal |publisher=Philipp von Zabern |location=Mainz |year=1998 |pages=204\u2013207 |isbn=3-8053-2313-1 |language=pt}}\n* {{citation |first=Felix |last=Teichner |title=Zwischen Land und Meer \u2013 Entre tierra y mar. Studien zur Architektur und Wirtschaftsweise l\u00e4ndlicher Siedlungen im S\u00fcden der r\u00f6mischen Provinz Lusitanien |publisher=Stvdia Lvsitana 3 (MNAR) / Madrider Beitr. (DAI) |year=2008 |isbn=978-84-612-7893-0 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |first=Walter |last=Trillmich |first2=Annette |last2=N\u00fcnnerich-Asmus |title=Hispania Antiqua \u2013 Denkm\u00e4ler der R\u00f6merzeit |publisher=von Zabern |location=Mainz |year=1993 |isbn=3-8053-1547-3 |language=German}}\n* {{citation |last=Botto |first=C. Pereira |contribution= Iconografia parcial das constru\u00e7\u00f5es de Milreu |title=O Archeologo Portugu\u00eas |year=1898 |pages=158 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=Rosa |first=J. Cunha |title=Anais do Municipio da Faro |issue=I |year=1969 |language=Portuguese}}\n* {{citation |last=Veiga |first=S.P.M. Est\u00e1cio da |title=A t\u00e1bua de bronze de Aljustrel |location=Lisbon, Portugal |year=1880 |language=Portuguese}}\n\n[[Category:Roman villas in Portugal]]\n[[Category:National monuments in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Faro, Portugal]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: 1990's \u2192 1990s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Ruins_of_Milreu"}
{"title_page": "Grace Rolek", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name         = Grace Rolek\n| image        = Grace Rolek by Gage Skidmore.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption      = Rolek at [[Phoenix Comicon]] in November 2017\n| birth_name   = Grace Sakura Rolek<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gracerolek.com/about |title=About Grace Rolek |accessdate=November 13, 2017 |publisher=GraceRolek.com}}</ref>\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1997|10|10}}\n| birth_place  = [[Burbank, California]], U.S.\n| death_date   = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|death date\u2020|birth date\u2020}} -->\n| death_place  = \n| other_names  = \n| occupation   = Actress, voice actress, singer\n| years_active = 2004\u2013present\n| known_for    = \n| website      = {{url|gracerolek.com}}\n| home_town    = [[Valencia, California]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Grace Sakura Rolek''' (born October 10, 1997) is an American actress, voice actress and singer.\n\n==Career==\nRolek is known for voicing Connie Maheswaran on ''[[Steven Universe]]'', as well as for appearing in ''[[Happiness Is a Warm Blanket, Charlie Brown]]'' and ''[[Final Fantasy VII: Advent Children]]''. She also made voice acting appearances in ''[[Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs (film)|Cloudy with a Chance of Meatballs]]'', ''[[Kung Fu Panda: Secrets of the Furious Five]]'' and ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://myfanfest.com/phoenix/project/grace-rolek/ |title=Grace Rolek - Phoenix Fan Fest |accessdate=November 13, 2017 |publisher=Phoenix Fan Fest |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171113165758/https://myfanfest.com/phoenix/project/grace-rolek/ |archive-date=November 13, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nShe made several public appearances as a guest of many [[Fan convention|fan conventions]] and gatherings, such as Cartoon Fair in France, or Beach City Con in Virginia Beach.\n\n==Personal life==\nRolek was born on October 10, 1997 in [[Burbank, California]] and began her career in voice acting in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm1728847/ |title=Grace Rolek - IMDb |accessdate=November 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe is of African-American, Italian, Polish and Japanese descent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/grace_rolek/status/895099933233041408 |title=This is something I've wanted to bring up publicly for a while now, but uhhhh I'm mixed lmao (thread)|accessdate=October 12, 2018|website= Twitter |author= Grace Rolek}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|+ Television roles\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[George Lopez (TV series)|George Lopez]]''\n|Sara\n|Episode: \"E.I.? E.I. OH\"\n|-\n|2006\u20132008\n|''Lou and Lou: Safety Patrol''\n|Louise (voice)\n|Main role\n|-\n|2008\n|''[[Handy Manny]]''\n|Nelson (voice)\n|Episode: \"Bake Sale/Camping Tools\"\n|-\n|2009\n|''[[Special Agent Oso]]''\n|Molly (voice)\n|Episode: \"To Grandma with Love/Gold Flower\"\n|-\n|2013\u20132019\n|''[[Steven Universe]]''\n|[[List of Steven Universe characters#Connie Maheswaran|Connie Maheswaran]] (voice)\n|Main role\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Steven Universe Future]]''\n|Connie Maheswaran (voice)\n|Episode: \"Bismuth Casual\", \"Together Forever\", \"Growing Pains\", \"Everything\u2019s Fine\", \"I Am My Monster\", \"The Future\"\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n|+ Film roles\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n|1984\n|''[[Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind (film)|Nausica\u00e4 of the Valley of the Wind]]''\n|Child (voice)\n|English dub\n|-\n|1995\n|''[[Whisper of the Heart]]''\n|Additional voices\n|English dub\n|-\n|2004\n|''U.S. Air Marshals''\n|Little Girl\n|Short film\n|-\n|2004\n|''[[Mulan 2]]''\n|Additional voices\n|Direct-to-video\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Tarzan 2]]''\n|Additional voices\n|Direct-to-video\n|-\n|2005\n|''[[Lilo & Stitch 2: Stitch Has a Glitch]]''\n|Additional voices\n|Direct-to-video\n|-\n|2005\